Let's explore the main differences between SVG and Canvas elements.


KEY DISTINCTIONS

 * Accessibility: svg: can be used for charts, graphs, etc where data resides in
   a database, canvas: data stay exclusively in memory, data is transient, e.g.
   a game character's position.

 * Coordinate System: svg: uses a cartesian coordinate system, canvas: can adopt
   different systems.

 * Saved States: svg: maintains a stack of saved states, canvas: doesn't.

 * Rendering Actions: svg: exhibits immediate rendering only, canvas: supports
   both immediate rendering and retained-mode like KB and KR.

 * Custom-Drawn Shapes: svg: does not support custom-drawn shapes natively,
   canvas: facilitates custom-drawn shapes.

 * Interactivity: svg: offers built-in interactivity features, canvas: requires
   manual handling.


COMMON FEATURES

 * Clearing Elements: canvas: clearRect(x, y, width, height), svg: using JS, can
   remove all children of an element.

 * Text Rendering: Both elements cater to text rendering through methods like
   fillText() (canvas) and SVG text elements.

 * Color Representation: Both adhere to the CSS color model.


K-DOMINANCE PRINCIPLE

canvas supports k-rendering and k-behavior for user interactions. svg supports
k-rendering for a tree representation of the drawing elements.


CODE EXAMPLE: K-DOMINANCE WITH CANVAS AND SVG

Here is the JavaScript code:

// Canvas: k-rendering, k-behavior
const canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
ctx.fillStyle = 'red';
ctx.arc(50, 50, 10, 0, Math.PI * 2);
ctx.fill();

// SVG: k-rendering
const svgElement = document.querySelector('svg');
const svgNS = "http://www.w3.org/2000/svg";
const svgCircle = document.createElementNS(svgNS, 'circle');
svgCircle.setAttribute('cx', 100);
svgCircle.setAttribute('cy', 100);
svgCircle.setAttribute('r', 10);
svgCircle.setAttribute('fill', 'green');
svgElement.appendChild(svgCircle);

Modern web applications often use forms to interact with users. By embracing
HTML5 form elements, developers can construct highly functional and visually
appealing interfaces.


CORE COMPONENTS

 1. form: Caption both static and dynamic content inside a form field.
 2. input: Multi-purpose control that enables text input (including password
    fields), checkbox selection, and radio button selection.

 * Type: Specifies data format (e.g., text, email, number).

 3. textarea: Enables multi-line text entry.
 4. select: Uses a drop-down list with optional associated <option> elements.


BASIC ATTRIBUTES

 * Name: Identifies the field when processing the form.
 * Id: Unique identifier, primarily for styling or JavaScript manipulations.
 * For: For labels, associates the label with a specific input element.


ADVANCED FUNCTIONALITY

 1. Grouping and Selection:

    * fieldset: Groups related elements and can include a legend.
    * legend: Descriptive caption for elements within a fieldset.
    * Checkbox: Enables multiple-item selection in the form of checkboxes.
    * Radio: Allows single-item selection with radio buttons.

 2. Buttons: Including specialized button, reset, and submit elements:

    * button: Designed for custom functionality via scripting.
    * reset: Clears form fields.
    * submit: Dispatches form data to the server.

 3. Labeling:

    * label: Assigns a context-aware label to a form element.
    * datalist: Provides a list of pre-defined options for an input element.

 4. Validation:

    * required: Mandates population of the input field.
    * pattern: Validates the field content using a regular expression.
    * min, max, minlength, maxlength: Introduce different constraints on the
      field content.


TEMPLATE AND FORM VALIDATION

Here is the HTML code:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>HTML5 Form Demo</title>
  <style>
      input:invalid {
          border: 2px solid red;
      }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <form action="/submit" method="post">
      <fieldset>
          <legend>Personal Information:</legend>
          <label for="name">Name:</label>
          <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required>
          <br>
          <label for="email">Email:</label>
          <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required>
      </fieldset>
      <br>
      <input type="submit" value="Submit">
  </form>
</body>
</html>



KEY COMPONENTS

 * Fieldset and Legend: Provide semantic grouping and labeling, enhancing
   accessibility.
 * Label Elements: Enhance form accessibility, especially for users with visual
   or motor impairments.
 * Input Types: Such as text, email, and required are for proper form input and
   validation.
 * Action and Method Attributes: Determine where data is sent and how,
   especially in server-side processing.### Prerequisites

To set up the required tools, install the following:

 * Node.js: Used for server-side JavaScript. Download and install Node.js from
   the official Node.js website [https://nodejs.org/en/].

Here is the Node.js code:

const http = require('http');
const fs = require('fs');
const port = 3000;

http.createServer((req, res) => {
  if (req.url === '/submit' && req.method === 'POST') {
    let body = '';
    req.on('data', chunk => {
      body += chunk.toString(); //convert Buffer to string
    });
    req.on('end', () => {
      console.log(body);
      res.end('Form data received');
    });
  } else {
    fs.readFile('form.html', (err, data) => {
      if (err) {
        res.writeHead(404, {'Content-Type': 'text/html'});
        return res.end('404 Not Found');
      }
      res.writeHead(200, {'Content-Type': 'text/html'});
      res.write(data);
      return res.end();
    });
  }
}).listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server running at http://localhost:${port}/`);
});

For adding CC (Closed Captions) or subtitles to your HTML5 video, the WebVTT
(Web Video Text Tracks) standard serves as a robust solution.


KEY WEBVTT COMPONENTS

 * Cues: These are snippets of text to be displayed in sync with the video. Each
   cue has a start time, an end time, and the associated text.
 * Cue Settings: Intuitive cues settings such as position, line, size, and
   alignment.


WEBVTT FILE EXTENSION

WebVTT files can use the .vtt file extension. These can be created and edited
using a standard text editor.

Here is an example:

<video id="video" controls>
  <source src="movie.mp4" type="video/mp4">
  <track label="English" kind="subtitles" srclang="en" src="subtitles_en.vtt" default>
  <track label="Korean" kind="subtitles" srclang="kr" src="subtitles_kr.vtt">
  <!--...additional sources as needed...-->
</video>



ALTERNATIVE APPROACH: JAVASCRIPT TIMESTAMPS

For more granular control over when subtitles appear, you can use JavaScript to
synchronize the video and subtitle text:

<video id="video" controls>
  <source src="movie.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video>

<div id="subtitle-area">
  <p id="subtitle">Subtitle Text</p>
  <!--...Additional subtitle cues...-->
</div>


And the JavaScript:

const video = document.getElementById('video');
const subtitleArea = document.getElementById('subtitle-area');
video.addEventListener('timeupdate', () => {
  // Find the current cue and display it in 'subtitleArea'
});


This allows for manual synchronization with the video.

For a more dynamic experience, each cue can be wrapped in a <div> that is only
displayed when that cue is active or within an active time window.


FULL JAVASCRIPT IMPLEMENTATION

Here is the full JavaScript method for handling subtitles:

<video id="video" controls>
    <source src="movie.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video>

<div id="subtitle-area">
</div>

<script>
    const video = document.getElementById('video');
    const subtitleArea = document.getElementById('subtitle-area');
    const tracks = video.textTracks;

    function displayCueText(cue) {
        subtitleArea.textContent = '';
        const cueDiv = document.createElement('div');
        cueDiv.textContent = cue.text;
        subtitleArea.appendChild(cueDiv);
        cueDiv.addEventListener('animationend', removeCue); // Add CSS to customize the style
    }

    function removeCue(event) {
        event.target.remove();
    }

    function setCue(index) {
        const activeCue = index < 0 ? null : tracks[0].cues[index];
        displayCueText(activeCue);
    }

    let lastCueIndex = -1;
    function updateCueDisplay() {
        let newCueIndex = -1;
        const time = video.currentTime;
        const cues = tracks[0].cues;
        for (let i = 0; i < cues.length; i++) {
            if (cues[i].startTime <= time && cues[i].endTime >= time) {
                newCueIndex = i;
                break;
            }
        }

        if (newCueIndex !== lastCueIndex) {
            lastCueIndex = newCueIndex;
            setCue(newCueIndex);
        }
    }

    video.addEventListener('timeupdate', updateCueDisplay);
</script>

Media Queries in HTML5 enable websites to customize their appearance and
behavior to suit different devices and screen sizes.


WHAT ARE MEDIA QUERIES?

Media Queries are conditional statements within style sheets that define when
and how specific styles should apply. They use logical operators to match a web
document against predefined media types, such as screen or print, as well as
media features like max-width and orientation.

Predicated style declaration:

/* If the viewport width is less than 600 pixels, apply these styles */
@media screen and (max-width: 600px) {
  body {
    background-color: lightblue;
  }
}



WHY USE MEDIA QUERIES?

 1. Responsive Design: Media Queries are fundamental to responsive web design,
    optimizing layouts for various devices, from smartphones to desktops.

 2. Bandwidth Optimization: Content, like images and videos, can be
    conditionally loaded based on device characteristics, aiding in bandwidth
    efficiency.

 3. Enhanced User Experience: Customizing fonts, colors, and layouts ensures a
    consistent, high-quality user experience across multiple platforms.

 4. CSS Optimization: Media Queries help ensure CSS rules are only applied when
    necessary, avoiding unnecessary processing and optimizing page speed.


CORE CONCEPTS

 * Media Types: Represent the type of media the style is intended for; common
   types include all, screen, print, and speech.

   @media print {
     /* Styles for printed output */
   }


 * Media Features: Characteristics of the viewing device used to conditionally
   apply styles.

   * min-width and max-width: Trigger styles based on viewport width.
   * orientation: Alter styles based on device orientation, such as landscape or
     portrait.


COMMON USE CASES

 * Adjusting Layouts: For example, adapting a menu from horizontal to vertical
   on smaller screens.

   @media (max-width: 768px) {
     .menu {
       flex-direction: column;
     }
   }


 * Responsive Images: By setting max-width on images, they won't exceed the
   viewport's width.

   img {
     max-width: 100%;
   }


 * Precision Typography: Tailoring fonts for clear, legible text on specific
   devices.

   @media (min-width: 800px) {
     body {
       font-size: 18px;
     }
   }



BEST PRACTICES

 * Mobile-First Approach: Construct styles for smaller screens first, then use
   media queries to cater to larger screens.

 * Test Across Devices: Validate styles across various devices to ensure
   consistent, optimized experiences.

You can create a navigation bar by utilizing an unordered list <ul> paired with
list items <li>. By combining these elements within a <nav> container, you
define a standardized and accessible navigation interface.


CODE EXAMPLE: BASIC NAVIGATION

Here is the HTML:

<nav>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
        <li><a href="/about">About</a></li>
        <li><a href="/services">Services</a></li>
        <li><a href="/contact">Contact</a></li>
    </ul>
</nav>



COMMON CSS STYLING

TRADITIONAL APPROACH

You can write custom CSS to transform the HTML structure into a stylish
navigation bar.

Here is sample CSS:

<style>
    nav ul {
        list-style-type: none;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
        overflow: hidden;
        background-color: #333;
    }

    nav li {
        float: left;
    }

    nav li a {
        display: block;
        color: white;
        text-align: center;
        padding: 14px 16px;
        text-decoration: none;
    }

    nav li a:hover {
        background-color: #ddd;
        color: black;
    }
</style>



MODERN FLEXBOX STYLING

With Flexbox, aligning and distributing navigation links becomes more
straightforward and responsive.

Here is the CSS:

<style>
    nav ul {
        list-style-type: none;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
        display: flex;
        justify-content: space-around;
        background-color: #333;
    }

    nav li a {
        color: white;
        padding: 14px 16px;
        text-decoration: none;
    }

    nav li a:hover {
        background-color: #ddd;
        color: black;
    }
</style>



KEY TAKEAWAY

Having a structured HTML foundation enables consistent navigation, while CSS
brings aesthetics and functionality. Stratified CSS methodologies such as
traditional and Flexbox present varied stylistic options.

The CSS for a slidedown style menu typically includes using opacity, transition,
and max-height to smoothly reveal and hide menu items.

This specific technique is ideal for small screen devices, like smartphones. It
provides an intuitive and space-efficient navigation experience. Each list item
in the menu can expand to show its children when clicked.


HTML STRUCTURE

Here is the HTML code:

<nav>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
    <li>
      <a href="#">Products</a>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="#">Category 1</a></li>
        <li><a href="#">Category 2</a></li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="#">Services</a>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="#">Service 1</a></li>
        <li><a href="#">Service 2</a></li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
  </ul>
</nav>



CSS FOR SLIDING MENU

Here is the CSS code:

nav ul {
  padding: 0;
  list-style: none;
  background: #f2f2f2;
}

nav ul li {
  display: block;
  position: relative;
  float: left;
  border-right: 1px solid #ccc;
}

nav ul li a {
  display: block;
  padding: 5px 10px;
  color: #333;
  text-decoration: none;
}

nav ul ul {
  display: none;
  position: absolute;
  top: 30px;
}

nav ul li:hover > ul {
  display: inherit;
}

nav ul ul li {
  width: 150px;
  float: none;
  display: list-item;
  position: relative;
}


JAVASCRIPT FOR SMOOTH ANIMATIONS

Here is the JavaScript code:

const dropdowns = document.querySelectorAll('nav ul li');

dropdowns.forEach(dropdown => {
  dropdown.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopPropagation();
    const siblings = dropdown.parentNode.children;
    Array.from(siblings).forEach(sibling => {
      if (sibling !== dropdown) {
        sibling.querySelector('ul').style.display = 'none';
      }
    });
    dropdown.querySelector('ul').style.display === 'none' ? dropdown.querySelector('ul').style.display = 'inherit' : dropdown.querySelector('ul').style.display = 'none';
  });
});

document.addEventListener('click', () => {
  dropdowns.forEach(dropdown => {
    dropdown.querySelector('ul').style.display = 'none';
  });
});

