customElements.define('custom-element', CustomElement);

Server-Sent Events (SSE) are unidirectional communication channels that enable
servers to push updates to clients over HTTP protocols. The client establishes
an HTTP or HTTPS connection to the server, and the server uses this connection
to push updates using a specific event format.


SSE EVENT TYPES

 * Data Events: Used for sending actual data. Clients can listen for these
   events via the onmessage event listener.
 * Connection Termination Events: Typically sent when the server wants to close
   the connection. Clients can handle this event using the onerror or onmessage
   event listener.


EVENT FORMAT

SSE events are divided into three parts:

 1. Identifier (optional): Kind of like a tag to group events. The identifier,
    if present, is prepended with id:. An example of an ID is id:abcdefg.
 2. Event Type (optional): This differentiates events based on a predetermined
    type. It is prepended with event:. For instance, an event type could be
    event:new-message.
 3. Data: The actual content of the event. This is mandatory unless the server
    wants to terminate the connection using a connection termination mechanism.

Here is the example of the server expression

response.write(`id:${eventId}\n`);  // Optional event ID
response.write(`event:newMessage\n`); // Optional event type
response.write(`data: ${JSON.stringify(message)}\n\n`);


If you are using an Express server, you can simply use the following syntax to
push data to the client:

app.get("/events", (req, res) => {
  let eventId = 1;
  res.setHeader("Content-Type", "text/event-stream");
  setInterval(() => {
    res.write(`id:${eventId}\n`);
    res.write("event:newMessage\n");
    res.write(`data:${JSON.stringify({ id: eventId, message: `This is message ${eventId}` })}\n\n`);
    eventId++;
  }, 1000);
});



BROWSER-SIDE HANDLING

To receive server-sent events, you perform the following on the client end:

 * Establish a Connection: Use the EventSource API, which takes in the URL for
   the source.
 * Handle Data Events: Utilize the onmessage event listener.
 * Handle Connection Termination: Use onerror or onmessage event listeners for
   that purpose.

Here is the JavaScript code for the client:

const eventSource = new EventSource("http://yourserver.com/events");

eventSource.onmessage = function (event) {
    console.log("New message received:", JSON.parse(event.data));
};

eventSource.onerror = function () {
    console.log("The connection encountered an error or was closed.");
};



WHEN TO USE SSE

Server-Sent Events are ideal for use-cases that involve one-way traffic or event
streaming, such as real-time notifications, live scores, news feeds, and stock
market updates.

However, they might not be suitable for more complex or interactive applications
that require duplex communication or frequent, small-data exchanges. For such
scenarios, WebSocket or AJAX could be more appropriate.

The Geolocation API provides web applications with a user's geographical
location. It achieves this through the device's GPS or other means like IP
address, cellular and WiFi network data, or Bluetooth.


COMPONENTS OF GEOLOCATION

The Geolocation API is composed of three essential parts:

 1. User Permission: Browsers usually request user consent before sharing
    location data.
 2. Geolocation Information: Once permission is granted, the geolocation data
    (latitude, longitude, altitude, and more) becomes accessible.
 3. Error Handling: The API offers mechanisms to handle failed attempts to
    obtain location information, such as limited or disabled location services.


CODE EXAMPLE: USING THE GEOLOCATION API

Here is the JavaScript code:

// Request current position
navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(
    successCallback,
    errorCallback,
    {
        enableHighAccuracy: true,
        timeout: 5000,
        maximumAge: 0
    }
);

// Success callback
function successCallback(position) {
    console.log(`Latitude: ${position.coords.latitude}, Longitude: ${position.coords.longitude}`);
}

// Error callback
function errorCallback(error) {
    switch(error.code) {
        case error.PERMISSION_DENIED:
            console.log('User denied the request for Geolocation.');
            break;
        case error.POSITION_UNAVAILABLE:
            console.log('Location information is unavailable.');
            break;
        case error.TIMEOUT:
            console.log('The request to get user location timed out.');
            break;
        default:
            console.log(`An unknown error occurred: ${error.message}`);
    }
}



PRIVACY CONSIDERATIONS

Using location-based services raises privacy concerns, and users should be
informed and agree to share their location. When the browser requests location
data, it prompts the user with a permission request, and the user can choose to
allow or deny access. Some web browsers may even give users finer control over
the accuracy and persistence of location data.

The Fullscreen API allows web developers to request, exit, and monitor
fullscreen modes for HTML elements. Utilizing this API can offer a more
immersive user experience in applications such as games or video players.


FEATURES AND BENEFITS

 * Compatibility: The API is supported across various modern browsers, including
   Chrome, Firefox, Edge, and Safari.
 * Keyboard Interaction: Even in fullscreen mode, users can employ keyboard
   shortcuts, aiding both accessibility and familiarity.
 * Developer Control: Access to the API is granted only when summoned via user
   interaction or a trusted event handler.


IMPLEMENTATION EXAMPLE: FULLSCREEN VIDEO PLAYER

Here is the HTML5 code:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Fullscreen Video Player</title>
  <style>
    #video-container {
      position: relative;
      width: 70%;
      margin: auto;
    }
    video#fullscreen-enabled[controls]::-webkit-media-controls {
      display: none;
    }
    #fullscreen-button {
      position: absolute;
      top: 20px;
      right: 20px;
      z-index: 1;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

<div id="video-container">
  <video id="fullscreen-enabled" controls>
    <source src="video.mp4" type="video/mp4">
    Your browser does not support HTML5 video.
  </video>
  <button id="fullscreen-button">Full-Screen</button>
</div>

<script>
  const videoElem = document.getElementById('fullscreen-enabled');
  const fullscreenButton = document.getElementById('fullscreen-button');

  fullscreenButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
    if (videoElem.requestFullscreen) {
      videoElem.requestFullscreen();
    } else if (videoElem.webkitRequestFullscreen) {  // Safari
      videoElem.webkitRequestFullscreen();
    }
  });
</script>

</body>
</html>

Absolutely. There are plenty of JavaScript libraries available to elevate your
HTML interactivity. Each has distinct features and benefits, so you can choose
the one that best aligns with your needs. Here are some of the popular ones:

 * JQuery: A fast, small, and feature-rich JavaScript library. It simplifies
   HTML document traversing, event handling, and animation.

 * Lodash, offers some great shuffle functions

 * Moment.js: a date and time manipulation library, very popular

 * Chart.js and D3 for Charting and Graphing. D3 is quite advanced and flexible.


CODE EXAMPLE: JQUERY CLEAR WARNINGS

Here is the JQuery code:

$('#warning').click(function(){
  $(this).hide();
});


Here is the pure JavaScript code:

document.getElementById('warning').addEventListener('click', function(){
  this.style.display = 'none';
});


You have the option to use JQuery or Plain JavaScript for these operations. Both
achieve the same result, allowing you to make an informed choice based on your
specific requirements.
